dataIdInfo.idPurp: The Bureau of Ocean Energy Management (BOEM) collaborated with the Center for Geospatial Science and Technology (CGST) from 2020 to 2021 to generate a series of processed datasets to aid in renewable energy planning. Several variables important to offshore wind planning were summarized including wind speed, depth, slope, distance to shore etc. Datasets were summarized by BOEM aliquots, a 1200x1200 meter grid, covering the California, Oregon, and Washington coasts. In addition to a set of summarized attributes at the Aliquot Grid level, additional data deliverables were produced, such as processed reference data. All work was conducted in close cooperation with BOEM staff.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The wind speed “annual average” data found in this aliquot grid polygon dataset was derived by calculating the combined average of monthly (24 hour) and monthly (5pm-9pm) wind speed values contained in ~2km resolution wind speed point data sourced from the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL)*. These resulting values were then respectively added as new "Annual_Avg" and "Annual_Avg_5_9pm" attributes in the source wind speed dataset. These values were then interpolated by performing inverse distance weighted (IDW) interpolation, extracted to the aliquot centroids, and, finally, joined to the aliquot grid polygon dataset.

* The NREL source wind speed data contains hourly averages for each month and does not contain separate annual average attributes that covers the entire extent of the dataset (available for CA coastal region, not available for OR/WA coastal region).

The wind speed “number of months above 7 meters per second” data was derived by running the above noted monthly (24 hour) and monthly (5pm-9pm) data through a Python script that counts the number of months where the average wind speed is above 7 m/sec. The script then accordingly placed the values of these counts into "No_Month_Avg_Above_7" and "No_Month_Avg_5_9_Above_7" fields.

The extent of this data covers all of the U.S. Pacific coast aliquot grids with the exception of the southernmost region, south of ~32°N to ~31°N and between 118°W and ~120°W. This is due to the lack of available source wind speed data for the area.
